  digest: r-jClrVcEzQEC1EIIE7eIYv2LrPa2hE2J1niAbIVj8U
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  Small (~700 LoC) crate from the rust-cli org providing core ANSI styling
  types (Style, Color, Effects, Reset). Read every .rs file under src/ plus
  Cargo.toml, README, and the dump-style example.
  
  Supply-chain (#1): Clean. No build.rs (`build = false` in Cargo.toml), no
  proc-macros, no deps, no I/O, no env reads, no `Command`, no obfuscation.
  Only `include_str!` is the README for doctest. Licensed MIT OR Apache-2.0,
  repo link matches rust-cli/anstyle.
  
  Unsafe (#2): One `unsafe` block: `DisplayBuffer::as_str` at color.rs:614
  calls `core::str::from_utf8_unchecked` on `&self.buffer[0..self.len]`.
  SAFETY comment reads "Only `&str` can be written to the buffer" — this
  is slightly inaccurate because `write_code` (color.rs:589) writes raw u8
  values (`b'0' + digit`), not `&str` slices. The invariant still holds:
  `digit ∈ 0..=9` so the bytes are `b'0'..=b'9'` (ASCII, valid UTF-8), and
  the buffer is zero-initialized by `Default`. Functionally safe; the
  comment could be tighter (e.g. "all writes produce ASCII bytes").
  
  Miri (#3): Published tarball does not include CI configuration, so I
  cannot verify miri runs upstream. The unsafe is pure-Rust and trivially
  miri-testable. Capping at `positive` per rubric.
  
  Correctness (#4): `DisplayBuffer` capacity is 19 bytes, matching the
  longest possible output `\x1B[38;2;255;255;255m` (verified by the
  `max_display_buffer` test). `write_code` correctly handles all u8
  values (0..=255) by suppressing leading zeros while always printing
  at least one digit. No off-by-one issues spotted. No panicking
  arithmetic on user-controlled values; the only indexing is internal
  and bounded by the layout above.
