package:
  source: https://crates.io
  name: async-stream-impl
  version: 0.3.6
  revision: b0b2f22df8e87b7fed7b2fa234509797adbff7db
  digest: iVJffdUOUGyW_6ws6OjRIX0ZQLT_5_YapUISA9idAYc
review:
  thoroughness: medium
  understanding: high
  rating: positive
comment: |-
  The proc-macro half of the tokio-rs/async-stream crate, authored by Carl
  Lerche. A single src/lib.rs (~316 lines) plus Cargo.toml and LICENSE; no
  build.rs (the manifest sets `build = false`), no README, no examples in the
  tarball. Read the entire source.
  
  Concern #1 (malicious / suspicious): `proc-macro = true`, so this code runs
  in every consumer's build -- the threat surface that matters. Nothing
  alarming. The implementation is a straightforward syn/quote token-stream
  rewriter: it walks the user's block, swaps `yield <expr>` for
  `__yield_tx.send(...).await`, rewrites `?` inside `try_stream!` to forward
  the error through `__yield_tx`, and rewrites `for await x in stream` into a
  `Pin::new_unchecked` + `next()` loop. No I/O, no env-var reads, no Command,
  no include_bytes!, no obfuscation. Dependencies are the canonical
  proc-macro trio: proc-macro2 1.0.60, quote 1, syn 2.0.2 (full + visit-mut).
  License MIT, repository link matches tokio-rs/async-stream, version and
  authorship match crates.io.
  
  Concern #2 (unsafe + SAFETY): the macro body itself contains no executable
  `unsafe`. Three `unsafe` tokens appear inside `quote!` blocks -- i.e. they
  are emitted into the consumer's code, not run by the proc-macro:
    - lib.rs:176 `Pin::new_unchecked(&mut __pinned)` in the `for await`
      expansion (sound because `__pinned` is a fresh local immediately
      shadowed and never moved).
    - lib.rs:235 / lib.rs:271 `#crate_path::__private::yielder::pair()` in
      the generated `stream!` / `try_stream!` body.
  Audit of those unsafe invariants belongs to the async-stream crate review,
  not here. No cap from concern #2.
  
  Concern #3 (miri): the published tarball ships only the crate subdirectory
  -- no .github/, no CI config (CI lives at the workspace root of
  tokio-rs/async-stream). Since the proc-macro itself executes no unsafe
  code, miri coverage is not relevant to this crate. No cap.
  
  Concern #4 (correctness): walked the rewriter end-to-end. Observations:
    - `parse_input` (lines 16-24) panics via `input.next().unwrap()` and
      `_ => panic!()` if the first token tree isn't a Group containing the
      crate path. The macro is `#[doc(hidden)]` and only invoked by the
      `stream!` / `try_stream!` declarative macros in async-stream, which
      always prepend `($crate)`, so this precondition is enforced by the
      caller. Acceptable.
    - `attrs.pop().unwrap()` (line 171) is guarded by the
      `attrs.len() != 1` check three lines above.
    - `yield_expr.expr.as_ref().unwrap_or(&self.unit)` (line 119) has a
      proper fallback for bare `yield`.
    - The `stream`/`try_stream` ident special-case (lines 74-84) skips
      transformation inside nested `stream!`/`try_stream!` invocations to
      avoid double-rewriting nested yields; the matching `visit_macro_mut`
      override (lines 193-200) does the same at the syn level. Consistent.
    - The `'__async_stream_private_check_scope` label + dummy `if false`
      block (lines 226-232, 262-268) is a scope-check trick that forces the
      `break` target in the yield expansion to type-check; benign.
    - `replace_for_await` (lines 287-316) recurses into Groups by
      reconstructing them with `set_span` preserved -- span info is not lost.
  No reproducible bugs found.
  
  Rating: positive. Behaves as a thin syn/quote rewriter, no executable
  unsafe, no supply-chain red flags.
----- SIGN CREV PROOF -----
